    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:4fbf658e-0da6-4c17-b7cd-d56c0635049c",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 38-year-old woman who appears slightly older than her stated age, with a guarded but generally cooperative demeanor during clinical interviews. She often wears several mismatched layers of clothing regardless of the weather, and her grooming fluctuates from acceptable to mildly neglected depending on symptom severity. Eye contact is intermittent, and her speech is soft with occasional latency, especially when she seems distracted by internal stimuli. She reports hearing voices that comment on her actions and sometimes believes strangers are referring to her indirectly. During periods of worsening illness, her affect becomes noticeably blunted and she isolates herself in her apartment for days at a time.\n\nShe lives alone in subsidized housing and works limited part-time evening shifts stocking shelves at a grocery store, a position she has maintained with support from a community mental health team. Her routine is inconsistent. On stable days she prepares simple meals, waters her houseplants, sketches in a notebook, and listens to music. On more symptomatic days she sleeps irregularly, forgets to eat, and becomes suspicious of neighbors or people in public. She has a small social network and remains in intermittent contact with her mother and an older sister, both of whom help remind her about appointments and encourage treatment adherence.\n\n{patientName} describes herself as once more outgoing before psychiatric symptoms became prominent in her late twenties. She is currently single and has no children. She smokes cigarettes daily and drinks several cups of coffee per day, particularly when anxious or fatigued. She denies current alcohol misuse and says she stopped using cannabis years ago after noticing it worsened her paranoia. She prefers quiet environments, avoids crowded places when symptomatic, and takes walks early in the morning when she feels safer outdoors.\n\nFunctionally, {patientName} has chronic difficulties with concentration, motivation, and organizing daily tasks. She acknowledges recurring auditory hallucinations and paranoid thoughts, though insight varies with symptom control. She is not typically hostile, but she can become fearful and highly avoidant when psychosis intensifies. Her illness causes moderate impairment in occupational functioning, self-care consistency, and social relationships, though she retains some independence with community support."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:eacb0823-e526-44fe-bf30-46b1c16086b9",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} began to show gradual psychiatric decline in her late twenties, including increasing social withdrawal, suspiciousness, difficulty keeping up with work responsibilities, and reduced ability to organize daily activities. At age 30 she had her first clear psychotic episode marked by auditory hallucinations and persecutory beliefs, resulting in psychiatric hospitalization. Since then she has had two additional inpatient psychiatric admissions, most recently 3 years ago after discontinuing antipsychotic medication and becoming increasingly paranoid, sleep-deprived, and unable to manage basic self-care.\n\nHer outpatient course has been complicated by partial adherence to treatment, often due to poor insight, sedation from prior psychotropic regimens, and inconsistent attendance at follow-up visits. She currently receives case-management support and periodic psychotherapy focused on coping strategies, reality testing, and improving routine structure. She has no known history of seizure disorder, traumatic brain injury, or major neurologic illness. There are no documented suicide attempts, though she has endorsed passive hopelessness during low-mood periods and requires ongoing psychiatric risk assessment.\n\nRelevant medical issues include chronic tobacco use, overweight status, sedentary lifestyle, and intermittent constipation associated with low dietary fiber and prior medication effects. She was treated once for dehydration during a period of poor oral intake but has otherwise had no major nonpsychiatric hospitalizations. She reports past cannabis use in her twenties and early thirties but denies current illicit substance use. Menstrual cycles are regular, and she is not currently pregnant."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}